data.content:
Yes — your current cast will throw an `InvalidCastException` instead of a clean test failure if the type is wrong. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

`Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>` (MSTest v3+) gives a clear failure message like *"Expected type: EmailHandler, Actual type: SmsHandler"* instead of an exception. If you're on an older MSTest, use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler))`.
